Worker Node: These are the physical server or vm's which provides a resources like CPU, Memory,netwrok,storage etc 

             Application or containers runs on this worker nodes

Kubelet: It's a nodelevel working agent. 
         It start and run the containers It 
         Checks the pod specifications assigned to node
         Reports node and pod state to the control plane

Scheduler: It decides which pod should assign to the which node and decides the best node based on available cpu, memory, etc...

Controller manager: It matches the desired and the current state of the luster
                    It ensures the required no.of pods and running using replicas
                    Finds the node failure



Q:  Write a Deployment manifest for an nginx application with 2 replicas, and explain how Kubernetes maintains the desired number of Pods.

Ans:
Manifest file:

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: nginx-deployment
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: nginx
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: nginx
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: nginx
        image: nginx:latest
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80


The replica set ensure the required no.of runs at all the time in the way as

Controller manager starts the replica set controller. Then replica set controller checks the current state aganist the desired state mentioned in the manifest file and ensures that 2 pods are running at every time.
If we scale up the replicas then replica set controller add a fewer pods to ensure the required no.of pods are running at every time.
If we scale down the replicas to 1 then replica set controller delete 1 pod and ensures 1 pod is running at every time. 



Q: If a Pod is running but you cannot access it from outside the cluster, you need a Service of type NodePort or LoadBalancer.

Ans:
NodePort: Exposes the application on a port of each node’s IP, so you can reach it externally via <NodeIP>:<NodePort>.
LoadBalancer: On cloud providers, automatically provisions an external load balancer with a public IP.

Manifest file:

apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: nginx-service
spec:
  type: NodePort
  selector:
    app: nginx
  ports:
    - port: 80        # Service port (inside cluster)
      targetPort: 80  # Container port
      nodePort: 30080 # External port on each node (range: 30000–32767)

Working:

The Service selects Pods with label app: nginx.

Requests to http://<NodeIP>:30080 are forwarded to one of the Nginx Pods.

Kubernetes ensures load balancing across the 2 replicas.

If a Pod dies, the Service automatically routes traffic only to healthy Pods.


Q: Explain how you would store a database password securely in Kubernetes and inject it into a Pod.

Ans:
We use secrets in Kubernetes to store the password or any sensitive data in encrypted format(base64) and we used to refer this secret in deployment as an environment variable.

Steps:
1. firs we should create a secret manifest file to store the sensitive data.
2. next we should create a deployment manifest and refer secret as env variable 
3. Before referencing  teh secret we should encrypt the sensitive data in the base64 format and store it in teh secret manifst file by using the below command

echo -n <sensitive data> | base64      eg:echo -n "password123" | base64

Secret manifest:

apiVersion: v1
kind: Secret
metadata:
  name: db-secret
type: Opaque
data:
  db-password: cGFzc3dvcmQxMjM=   # base64 for "password123"


Deployment manifest file:

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: app-deployment
spec:
  replicas: 1
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: myapp
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: myapp
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: myapp
        image: myapp:latest
        env:
        - name: DB_PASSWORD
          valueFrom:
            secretKeyRef:
              name: db-secret
              key: db-password



Q: Your application receives sudden high traffic. Explain how the Horizontal Pod Autoscaler would help and what it needs to work.

Ans:
Horizontal Pod Autoscaler is used to auto scale the no.of pods based on the resources like CPU, Memory etc..
Whenever there is an increase in traffic the HPA scales up the pods count 
and whenever there is a decrease in traffic the HPA scales down the pods count to save the resources.

We can scales the pods count by HPA using a simple kubectl command or by using a manifest file


kubectl autoscale deployment nginx-deployment --cpu-percent=70 --min=2 --max=10

In the above command HPA ensures that min of 2 pods runs at every time and scales pods count up to 10 based on the CPU when it reaches 70%


HPA manifest file:

apiVersion: autoscaling/v2
kind: HorizontalPodAutoscaler
metadata:
  name: nginx-hpa
spec:
  scaleTargetRef:
    apiVersion: apps/v1
    kind: Deployment
    name: nginx-deployment
  minReplicas: 2
  maxReplicas: 10
  metrics:
  - type: Resource
    resource:
      name: cpu
      target:
        type: Utilization
        averageUtilization: 70
